On the pads, worked towards the leg side for a single.
FOUR! Good comeback by Rassie van der Dussen! Full ball on the middle and leg pole line, van der Dussen drives this one straight back down the ground through mid on for a boundary.

Another one which was almost chopped on! This is Ben Stokes at his best! Bouncer just outside off, van der Dussen looks to hop and defend. The ball goes off the inside edge onto the turf again but this time past the stumps. Van der Dussen survives and England smelling blood here.
Back of a length ball on off, Quinton de Kock punches this ball off the back foot towards cover for a single. Gets off the mark!
Quinton de Kock walks into bat. South Africa's hopes relies on him now. Can he script something special in this innings?

OUT! CHOPPED ON! Faf du Plessis departs after a fighting knock but for England, Ben Stokes is the man yet again! Stokes bowls a length ball just around off, it pitches and nips back in a bit. It also hits the crack and that makes the ball stay low. Faf du Plessis looks to come forward and defend but the ball goes off the bottom edge, onto the turf and then onto the middle pole to dislodge the bails. The skipper departs and a huge, huge blow for the Proteas!
Another ill-directed bouncer, Rassie lets it go.

Ouch! That might have sent shivers down the spine of Rassie van der Dussen. Wood goes short and directed on the body. Rassie looks to leave it by dropping hos wrists but the ball does not bounce as expected and it hits his chest hard. Rassie is onto his knees as he waits for the physio to attend to him.

Length and on off, pushed to cover off the back foot.

EDGED AND FOUR! That was an educational edge there. Rassie van der Dussen moves into the nervous 90s. The ball goes past him and into the fence at third man.

Van der Dussen pushes this one towards the mid on region and takes a single.

We are back after the Lunch Break. The South African batsmen Faf du Plessis and Rassie van der Dussen walk out to resume their innings. All eyes will be on the South African skipper as he has been short of runs. For England, Ben Stokes will start the session with the ball.

So, an important passage of play awaits us in Johannesburg. Can the South African batters hold fort and perform a miracle of some sorts or will England do what is looking inevitable? Join us at 1140 Local (0940 GMT) to find out!

29 overs, 90 runs and 2 wickets. That is what has happened in the morning session at Johannesburg on Day 4 and England will be happy with their performance so far. After a wicketless hour of play, Pieter Malan and Dean Elgar looked strong and confident. The Proteas were becoming hopeful that these two can stitch a good stand but right after the Drinks break, Woakes struck to dismiss Malan as he was caught in slips by Ben Stokes. Rassie van der Dussen walked in then, and he combined with the southpaw Dean Elgar to stitch a 50-run stand. However, right before the Lunch break, Stokes was again in the thick of things as he dismissed Elgar and England returned to the pavilion with smiles on their faces. South Africa would have loved if Elgar could have kept his wicket intact but it was not to be.

Just when it looks like South Africa are onto something England put a brakes on it and dampen all the hopes. The pitch is hardly doing anything but Stokes once again shows why he is held in high regards and produces something special.

BEATEN! Beauty of a nut there. Rassie is lured into poking this length ball outside off. Luckily he does not edge it behind.
Oh! The inside edge there. Rassie looks to defend this length ball off the back foot only to get an inside edge onto his pads.
FOUR! Short ball on middle and Rassie takes the full toll of it. He just pulls it with disdain and the ball races to the mid-wicket fence for a boundary.
Good length ball on off, Rassie blocks it off the back foot and into the ground.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Wide! Bouncer on middle and leg, Elgar ducks as it is way too high.
Woah! Jaffa by Curran! Bowls a back of a length delivery just outside off, and this time gets it to nip back in. Elgar looks to defend but the ball cuts him in half and oohs and aahs all around.
Full ball on the off pole line, defended back towards the bowler.
Outside off, Dean leaves this one alone.
Length ball on middle and off, Elgar defends it towards the man at mid off.
Good length ball on middle and off, defended back towards the bowler.
Sam Curran is back on.

Another huge appeal but this time the umpire shakes his head. Very full on off and it nips back in. Rassie looks to play but gets a feather on it onto the pads. The English players are once again excited but this time the umpire is not.

NOT OUT! Rassie survives. Good referral by the South African no. 3! He lives to fight another day. Good length ball pitching around off, van der Dussen looks to defend but misses. The ball hits him high on the pads of his back leg. The English players go up in a huge appeal and the umpire raises his finger. Rassie has a word with his partner and then signals the 'T'. Replay rolls in and first Ultra Edge confirms that there is no bat involved. Ball Tracker then rolls in and it shows that the ball is pitching in line, the impact though is Umpire's call. Then time to see whether the ball is hitting the stumps or not. It shows that the ball was going over the stumps.
Review time! Rassie van der Dussen is the man in question. The umpire has adjudged him out and it looks close to the naked eye. The Ball Tracker rolls in and shows that this is going OVER the stumps.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Outside off, left alone.
Good length ball on off, van der Dussen blocks it.
Rassie van der Dussen is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Malan departs and maybe it is a commentator's curse after all. Just as we said the openers cannot lose their concentration, Malan loses his focus, maybe the break in play brought about his downfall. Woakes is the man who has drawn first blood here. Full and wide outside off, Malan goes chasing after it like a kid chasing candy. He ends up getting a thick outside edge which goes to the right of Ben Stokes. You cannot keep him out of the game and he takes a good catch. Catching practice at slip for Big Ben. The steady opening stand has been taken down.

Drinks! A good solid hour for South Africa but they cannot afford to lose their concentration here. It is a long, long ask and the pair of Malan and Elgar need to keep on going for a big period of time. England will not be too disappointed with not getting a wicket in the first hour of play. They have plenty of runs to play with but they will look to strike at least a couple before the end of this session.
Good length ball on off, Malan pushes it wide of cover for a run. He will keep the strike.
Short ball, Malan ducks under it.

FOUR! Classic cover drive. You can keep on watching this shot on loop and you will continue to admire this every single time. Full around off, Malan gets on his front foot and leans into the cover drive. The outfield is quick so the fielder has no chance stopping that.
Outside off, Malan lunges forward and lets it carry to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle and leg, Malan once again plays it well as he glances it onto the ground towards short leg.
On the hips of Malan, he tucks it on the bounce to short leg.
Length ball on off, Malan pushes it wide of cover for one.
The batsman defends it from within the crease.
Woakes goes full on off, PM once again uses a dead bat to see it off.
On a length on off, Pieter defends this.
Fuller on off, Malan blocks it.
Absolute peach to end the over. Wood hits the deck hard outside off, it looks to be coming in with the angle but straightens up as it comes off the pitch. Elgar looks to defend but gets squared up.
After going short on the previous two balls, Wood goes very full on off. Elgar defends it to the left of the bowler. Wood goes to ground and gets his hand to it and deflects the ball to mid on.
Another short ball. This one is outside off and Dean sways away from it in a better way.
Bouncer! A very well-directed one by Wood. Elgar ducks under it awkwardly but no harm done.
Length delivery on off stump this time, Elgar defends this towards mid off.
FOUR! Just pure timing on this one! Good length delivery around off, Elgar hangs on his back foot and uses the pace of Wood and just taps it through point for a boundary.
FOUR! Another back of a length ball on off, Malan rocks back and cuts and it goes just above the man at gully and into the third man fence.
Back of a length ball outside off, left alone.
Outside off, Malan does not fiddle with it and leaves it alone.

This time a louder appeal by England but again turned down! Good length ball just outside off, Malan looks to defend but fails to do so. The ball lobs towards the man at silly point who takes the catch and appeals. The umpire again shakes his head as he reckons this one has come off the pads of Malan. England opt against taking the review. Ball Tracker comes in and shows it was hitting the pad and the impact was outside off.
Length ball outside off, left alone.
Good length ball outside off, Malan looks to bend and defend but he misses the ball and is hit on the thigh pad.
The batsman lets the ball go outside his off stump.
Length ball on middle and off, defended.

Another appeal turned down! Length ball down the leg side, Elgar looks to flick this one fine but fails to do so. The ball deflects off his thigh pad towards Pope at short leg. He takes the catch and the England players appeal but the umpire turns it down. Replays confirm it did not hit the bat nor the glove.
Another length ball which is outside off, Elgar does not fiddle with it.
Another one outside off, left alone.
Length ball outside off, Elgar leaves this one alone.

Outside off, Elgar leaves this one alone and gets through the over. South Africa have scored 25 runs at the end of the the first 10 overs of the day, but more importantly, they have not lost a single wicket so far.
Back of a length ball on the off side, defended towards the man at point for a single.
Length ball outside off, left alone.
The batsman flicks it away with a wristy shot.
Another one on the pads, played towards the man at mid-wicket.
On the pads, flicked towards the man at square leg.
Change from both the ends. Chris Woakes replaces Sam Curran from the other end.
Full ball on middle and off, Malan pushes it down the ground past the man at mid on and the batters take a couple to end the over.
Bouncer down the leg side, Malan ducks and lets it go.
Length ball on off, played towards the man at point.
Full ball on middle and off, defended back towards Wood.
Good length ball on middle and leg, defended towards the man at short leg.
Good running! Wood starts with a full ball on off, Elgar plays it with soft hands towards the off side and takes a very quick single. Intent!
First bowling change of the game. The hero with the ball from the first innings, actually the English hero and antagonist for South Africa in this game so far, Mark Wood is into the attack.
Another one on off and fuller in length, defended towards the man at mid off.
Fullish delivery around off, pushed to the man at mid off.
Once again on the pads, played towards square leg again but this time just a run.
FOUR! Well played but a bad ball! On the pads of Elgar, he flicks this one in the gap near square leg and the ball races away to the fence.
On the pads of Malan, he flicks this one towards the mid-wicket region and the batters take a single.
Good length ball on off, Malan plays a beautiful shot through the cover-point region and the batters take a couple.
Length ball outside off, left alone.
Length ball on off, defended towards the off side and Malan rotates strike.

Appeal turned down! Good length ball just outside off, coming in. Malan looks to defend this off the front foot but misses to get hit on the back leg's thigh pad. The England players appeal but nothing from the umpire. The impact looks outside off and Ball Tracker confirms it.
The batsman lets the ball go outside his off stump.
Another good length ball on the off side, this time Elgar defends it towards the off side with soft hands and takes a single.

Stuart Broad produces something special as soon as he comes around the wicket. Good length delivery just outside off, angling in. It pitches and nips away. Elgar looks to play at it but is completely beaten.
On the stumps, Malan defends it with a dead bat.
Full and swinging away from off, Elgar looks to defend but the ball takes the outside edge and rolls to third a for a single.
Full on off, Elgar pushes it to mid off.

Almost chopped on. Length ball just outside off. Elgar looks to cut but the ball is too close to the stumps and his body. He still goes for it, he ends up chopping it behind and luckily for him and his team the ball does not go onto hit the stumps.
Full on middle, Elgar strokes it to mid on.
Good length delivery outside off, Elgar lets it carry to the keeper.
Follows the boundary with a calm push to mid off.

FOUR! Beautiful drive from Malan. Slightly overpitched on off and middle, Malan gets in a good position on his front foot and drives it with class through mid off for a boundary. This will give him a lot of confidence.
Full on off, Malan pushes it to mid on.
Broad goes full and closer to the off pole. Malan defends it with surety.
Good length delivery outside off, asking Malan to have a crack but he calmly leaves it alone.

Huge appeal for LBW but probably going down the leg side. Full on middle and leg, it goes with the angle. Malan looks to flick but misses. There is a huge appeal from the English players but the umpire turns it down.
Good length delivery on middle and off, defended towards the off side by Elgar.
Length ball on middle and leg, Elgar looks to defend but is hit on the thigh pad.

EDGED AND FOUR! Good length ball down the leg side, Elgar looks to work it towards that side but the ball goes off the leading edge behind the man at point and into the fence for a boundary. First boundary of the innings.
Defended off the back foot towards the man at cover-point.
Good length ball on middle and leg, pushed towards the man at mid on.

Jaffa! What a delivery by Curran! A length delivery just outside off, angling in. It pitches and then goes away as Elgar looks to play at it. He is completely squared up but the ball beats his outside edge.
Good length delivery outside off, Malan leaves it alone to finish the over.
Length delivery outside off, left alone by Malan again.
First runs of the day! On the pads of Malan, he flicks this one towards square leg and gets a couple.
The batsman shoulders arms to let that one through.
Fuller ball on the off pole line, Malan looks to defend but the ball goes off the outer half towards the man at point all along the ground.
Length ball outside off to start the over by Malan, he leaves this one alone.
Outside off, left alone by Elgar.
Length ball outside off, Elgar defends this one towards the off side.
Good length ball on middle and off, Elgar defends this one onto the pitch and the ball goes above Curran and the man from mid off runs to his left to gather the ball.
Length ball outside off, left alone by Elgar.
Curran goes fuller, he defends this one towards the man at mid off.
Length ball on off to start with by Curran, Elgar defends it off the back foot towards the man at point.
Sam Curran to partner Stuart Broad from the other end.

Ohh! Good delivery to end the over! Length ball on off, angling in, Malan offers no stroke but the ball comes in too much and is hit near the box. End of a good over as England look to attack the Proteas straightaway.
Good length ball attacking the middle pole, Malan defends this one towards the man at mid on.
Fuller one on off by Broad, Malan pushes this one towards the man at cover.
Another full ball attacking the off pole, Malan shuffles across and defends this towards the mid-wicket fielder.
Back of a length ball on middle and off, left alone by Pieter Malan.
Broad starts the day with a full length ball attacking the stumps, Malan does well to defend this ball out.
